reviews.text: Very beautiful palace of the Amir of Bukhara.  Used to be the Summer palace. The Palace is really beautiful... Looks like palaces of St. petersberg or Moscow

The Khan's summer Palace built in a modern European style. The main courtyard and ball room are quite beautiful but otherwise the rest of the structure lacks maintenance. There's a nice reflecting pool behind the main building. Good photo op to catch the reflection in the water  mirroring the old Harum.

Avoid the vocal noisy coach parties by going midday or later. 3rd palace built by the last Emir using local and Russian talent. Unkempt gardens are rather pleasing giving it a melancholy end of an era air. Rather glad it’s not been sanitised and given the Disney effect. 
Relax at various points to take in views of the three main structures rather than trying to rush around like a a headless chicken.
I’m in love with this place

Interesting history and nice views from the top. But the space would perhaps be put to better use with clearer signage and curated exhibits to explain the significance of the Ark, than to install a number of bizarre, completely unrelated museums (e.g. "natural history").

The walls of the Ark, are uniquely shaped and constructed. It is a sight not to be missed in Bukhara. Inside the Ark, there are various museum exhibits, stables, a throne hall and other things to explore. Truly beautiful!
The place is majestic. Love the hall where the king used to receive guests and dignitaries

Cool from the outside, but going in isn't necessary.  I went just before closing, and all the museums inside were closed.  There wasn't much else to see as you can only visit a tiny portion of the fort.  I'm glad I had a guidebook with me to describe the 3-4 places open to the public.  Otherwise it would have been a waste of time and money.

O you wretches! This world is a guest-house. Every day thirty thousand witnesses put their signature to the decree "Death is a reality" with their corpses, and they testify to the assertion. Can you kill death? Can you contradict these witnesses? Since you can't, death causes people to say: "Allah! Allah!" Which of your guns and cannons can illuminate the everlasting darkness confronting someone in the throes of death in place of "Allah! Allah!", and transform his absolute despair into absolute hope? Since there is death and we shall enter the grave, and this life departs and an eternal life comes, if guns and cannons are said once, "Allah! Allah!" should be said a thousand times. And if it is in Allah's way, the gun also says "Allah!", and the cannon booms "Allahu Akbar!" It breaks the fast with "Allah," and starts it...

Ey bîçareler! Bu dünya bir misafirhanedir. Her günde otuzbin şahid, cenazeleriyle "El-mevtü hak" hükmünü imza ediyorlar ve o davaya şehadet ediyorlar. Ölümü öldürebilir misiniz? Bu şahidleri tekzib edebilir misiniz? Madem edemiyorsunuz; mevt, Allah Allah dedirtir. Sekeratta Allah Allah yerine; hangi topunuz, hangi tüfeğiniz, zulümat-ı ebedîyi o sekerattakinin önünde ışıklandırır, ye's-i mutlakını ümid-i mutlaka çevirebilir? Madem ölüm var, kabre girilecek; bu hayat gidiyor, bâki bir hayat geliyor. Bir defa top tüfek denilse; bin defa Allah Allah demek lâzım gelir. Hem Allah yolunda olsa; tüfek de Allah der, top da Allahu Ekber diye bağırır, Allah ile iftar eder, imsak eder.

Медресе Кукельдаш — медресе в Бухаре, входящее в ансамбль Ляби хауз. Было построено по распоряжению Кулбабы кукельташа, высокопоставленного сановника и известного мецената.

Медресе — самое крупное в Средней Азии, его размеры 86 х 69 метров. В медресе есть 130 худжр, здесь обучались и жили 320 студентов. 

В этом медресе в конце 19 века учился видный таджикский писатель Садриддин Айни.
